Enclave Options  - Used to enable AWS Nitro Enclaves, which are isolated secure environments inside an EC2 instance for running highly sensitive workloads like encryption, security processing, or confidential data handling.

enabled = true → turns ON Nitro Enclaves (extra secure mini-environment inside EC2)


enabled = false → enclaves are not used (default)


enclave_options {
  enabled = true

}

maintenance_optoins - Used to control what AWS should do if the EC2 instance has a hardware or host-level failure, especially whether it should automatically recover the instance or not.


auto_recovery = "default" -> AWS will automatically recover the instance if there is a failure 
auto_recovery =  "disabled" -> AWS will not recover it automatically ; you must handle it manually 


                     maintenance_options {
                       auto_recovery = "disabled" / "default"
                     }        


metadata_options - Used to control how the Ec2 instances metadata service works ,which provide internal info like IP ,region , IAM role and tags .It is mainly used for security and accesss control of that metadata

http_endpoint -> turn metadata_service on or off 
    enabled -> metadata accessible (default)
    disable -> block metadata access
http_protocol_ipv6 -> allow metadata access over ipv6
    enable / disablr (default is disabled)
http_put_response_hop_limit -> how far the metadata requests can travel inside the network 
    value : 1 to 60 (default is 1 , keep it low as possible )
http_token -> security mode for metadata access
     required -> must use token ( secure IMDSV2)
     optional -> no token needed (less secure and default)
instance_metadata_tags -> allow access to Ec2 tags via metadata 
     enable or disable (default is disable)


metadata_options {
  http_endpoint               = "enabled"
  http_tokens                 = "required"
  http_put_response_hop_limit = 2
  instance_metadata_tags      = "enabled"
}



instance_market_options - Used to decide how you want to buy the EC2 instance, like whether you want a cheaper “spot” instance or a reserved “capacity-block” type purchase.

market_type → type of purchase model
"spot" → cheap unused AWS capacity (can be stopped anytime ,default)
capacity-block" → reserved fixed capacity for a period

if you chooose the spot instance you will have extra setting 


network_interface - Used to attach a specific pre-created network interface (ENI) to an EC2 instance at boot time so you can control networking (IP, subnet, security group), but it is now deprecated because changing it can recreate the whole instance.

network_interface_id → ID of the network card (ENI) you want to attach
device_index → position of the network interface
    0 = main network interface (eth0)
    1,2... = extra interfaces
network_card_index → integer index of the network card .limitted by the instance type . The default index is 0
delete_on_termination -> whether to delete the network interface when instance is deleted (default : false) 


primary_network_interface  - Used to define the main network connection (eth0) of the EC2 instance by attaching a specific network interface to it; this is the primary way the instance connects to the network.

               primary_network_interface {
                 network_interface_id = "eni-1234"
               }
* network_interface_id -> ID of the main network card ( ENI ) 
* delete_on_termination -> tells AWS whether to delete it when instance is deleted (read-only here )


primary_network_interface {
  network_interface_id = "eni-123456"
}


secondary_network_interface - Used to attach extra network cards (ENIs) to an EC2 instance at launch time, usually for special networking needs like high-speed internal communication (RDMA) or separate private networks; these are separate from the main network interface.

secondary_subnet_id → subnet where the extra network card will be created
network_card_index → which physical network card slot to use (each slot holds one interface)
device_index → position of the interface inside the instance (default: 0)
interface_type → type of interface (always "secondary")
delete_on_termination → delete this network card when instance is deleted (default: true)
private_ip_address_count → number of private IPs to assign (default: 1)
private_ip_addresses → manually assign specific private IPs






